  "text": "Although we often think of rituals as religious, Durkheim argues that social rituals are moments of great emotional intensity that are crucial to all types of nonreligious integration of societies. Rituals make it possible to control and attach individuals to groups even when people are not in each other's presence. During the moments of jointly repeating common gestures, ideas and emotions circulate among group members like a kind of mental current flowing through everyone; this current attaches special \"moral charges\" to these ideas and feelings [CITATION_1] . This current (which we can experience as goose bumps, hair rising on the back of our neck, or a full and aching heart) helps focus individual attention intensely on others and on the life of the group.",
